Clinical documentation reviewed in PowerChart, 79-year-old female with history of dementia hyperlipidemia and hypothyroidism who presented to the Emergency Department with a chief complaint of chest pain.  The patient's daughter who was at bedside reported that around 2100 last night the patient was watching TV and began to look pale and ashy.  She reported symptoms like hot flashes and complained of left-sided chest discomfort.  The patient reported that this lasted briefly; however occurred a few more times intermittently in the following hour.  The patient reported a development of cough during that time.  The patient's daughter added that the patient had eaten dinner normally and took her night medications before symptom onset., Initial laboratory workup revealed a troponin of 2.46.  Other lab work was essentially unremarkable.  EKG showed evidence of new left bundle-branch block as compared with last EKG in 2011.  The patient was tachycardic with a heart rate of 110.  In the Emergency Department the patient developed dropping of oxygen saturation.  She was placed on BiPAP., CT chest showed no CT evidence of pulmonary embolus; however marked bilateral bronchial wall thickening consistent with bronchitis as well as pulmonary edema and mild trapping with moderate-sized bilateral pleural effusions.  The case was discussed with the cardiologist on call who initiated IV heparin and optimization of patient's medical therapy.  The patient received IV Lasix and admitted to the Intensive Care Unit., 02/21/17 CARDIOLOGY NOTE, Acute non-ST segment elevation myocardial infarction: She has a left bundle branch block so we cannot be certain as to the territory of ischemia. I had a lengthy discussion with 2 daughters (daughter who is a veterinarian by phone) yesterday. I don't think she is a good candidate for invasive evaluation given her advanced dementia. My recommendations are for dual platelet therapy beta blockers high-dose atorvastatin and ACE inhibitor. IF she were to have further chest pain or worsening heart failure could consider catheterization to see if something can be intervened upon but she would never be a surgical candidate. The other option would be for biventricular pacemaker-> she would never be an ICD candidate given the severity of her dementia. Will get up and ambulate today.  , Acute pulmonary edema: She has severe left ventricular dysfunction related to her left bundle branch block as well as underlying ischemic cardiomyopathy. Again I think medical therapy is all that is warranted. She remains on ACE inhibitor Aldactone Lasix beta blocker. Have increased Lasix to BID, Plan: Increase Furosemide,          Dual platelet therapy high-dose atorvastatin ACE inhibitor and beta blocker,          Aldactone plus the Lasix,          Ambulate in the halls,          Invasive evaluation/biventricular pacing only if symptoms prove refractory, MEETS INPATIENT  SLOW TO PROGRESS
